                                                    Food 4 Less/Foods Co Stores Launch Campaign to Benefit After-School Programs
                                                


                                                    PR Newswire – 
                                                    12:41 PM ET 07/17/2017
                                                


LOS ANGELES, July 17, 2017  Southern California-based Food 4 Less is pleased to announce that it is raising funds at the checkstands in its supermarkets to support after-school education programs. Southern California and greater Chicago, and Foods Co supermarkets in Central and Northern California. The after-school program fund-raising campaign will run through November 7, 2017.

















                                                    Ralphs Grocery Company Launches Charitable Campaign to Benefit After-School Programs
                                                


                                                    PR Newswire – 
                                                    11:36 AM ET 07/17/2017
                                                


LOS ANGELES, July 17, 2017 Ralphs Grocery Company is pleased to announce that it is raising funds to support after-school education programs in Southern California. Valerie Jabbar, president of Ralphs Supermarkets.

















                                                    BULLET: US TSY FLOWS: Treasuries drifted off session high....
                                                


                                                    Market News Intl Fixed Income Bullets – 
                                                    9:50 AM ET 07/17/2017
                                                


US TSY FLOWS: Treasuries drifted off session high prices after early front end bid, amid selling in intermediates, including in Tsy futures, said traders. The 30Y bond also got pushed down lower too amid selling; hit 102-02+/32 high price (2.897% session low yield) at 8:22am ET. Mild foreign bid also reported in Tsys. Earlier, Tsys had followed UK Gilts and German Bunds upward. The 3/10/30Y auctions all settle today, ushering in new supply into the overnight repo market. - Meanwhile it's likely corporate rate locks also provided some early Tsys pressure amid a long list of corporate bonds coming to market today, including Wells Fargo (WFC) 5Y, Citi 3-parter, American Honda 18M FRN and 3Y FXD/FRN, AerCap Ireland 10Y, Kroger (KR) 5/10/30Y, JPM 21Y, 31Y; and Sweden 4Y eyed for Tuesday. "Much of those deals would have been bank deals," said one trader. "So, they should have been swapped. That should support the market when the hedges get unwound."

















                                                    Kroger to contribute $1 billion to bolster underfunded pension plan
                                                


                                                    MarketWatch – 
                                                    9:26 AM ET 07/17/2017
                                                


Kroger Co. (KR) disclosed in a filing Monday that it will contribute up to $1 billion to pension plan, which it believes the "significantly" address the underfunded position of the plan. The supermarket chain said it plans to fund the contribution by issuing debt. The said certain participants' benefit balances will be distributed out of the plan, by way of a transfer to other qualified retirement plan options or a lump-sum payout.

















                                                    Kroger to make $1 billion contribution to its benefit plans
                                                


                                                    Reuters – 
                                                    9:19 AM ET 07/17/2017
                                                


- Kroger Co (KR) , the biggest U.S. supermarket operator, said on Monday it would make a contribution of up to $1 billion to its benefit plans to address the under-funded position of the plan. The company will issue debt to pay for the funding of the pension liability, Kroger (KR) said in a regulatory filing, adding that its overall balance sheet obligations will not change.













						                            
